bmo: Short answer: it’s by design.

- BMO_SOURCE is only meant to be set when you’re hacking on bmo itself (the source repo). It tells bmo where to mirror writes to bmo://tools and where to create self-improvement commits.
- When you run bmo from some other directory (i.e., using the installed binary), there’s no unambiguous “source repo” to point at. The runtime only guarantees BMO_HOME (where the installed tools live). It intentionally does not auto-set BMO_SOURCE outside the source tree to avoid writing/committing into the wrong place.

How to make it set
- Manually export it in your shell:
  - export BMO_SOURCE=/absolute/path/to/your/bmo/source
- Or wrap it:
  - alias bmo='BMO_SOURCE=/absolute/path/to/bmo/source bmo'
- If you run from the source repo with node index.mjs (or a dev script that sets it), BMO_SOURCE will be present there.

Quick distinction
- BMO_HOME: where the active runtime (installed tools) lives; always set by the binary.
- BMO_SOURCE: only set when you explicitly export it or when running from the source/dev setup; used to mirror edits and commits to the source repository.
You: That feels like a regression. Part of the point of the project is that BMO_SOURCE is always available so that when using the installed binary, bmo can add to both BMO_HOME and BMO_TOOLS. Could we hardcode ~/src/bmo to be the default, if the directory exists, but fall back to an explicitly-set BMO_SOURCE if there is one, and then finally fall back to nothing?
